an au&s;picious influence over the whole of
virtue. The prevailing temper of the mind
is formed by its mo&s;t frequent employ|ments.
Intercour&s;e with Supreme per|fection
cannot, therefore, but ennoble and
improve it. The pure love of God, natu|rally
<PB N="286" REF="295">
rally connects it&s;elf with the love of man.
Hence, devotion has been often found a
powerful in&s;trument, in humanizing the
manners of men, and taming their unruly
pa&s;&s;ions. It &s;mooths what is rough, and
&s;oftens what is &s;ierce, in our nature. It is
the great purifier of the affections. It in|&s;ipires
contempt of the low gratifications
belonging to animal life. It promotes a
humble and chearful contentment with
our lot; and &s;ubdues that eager de&s;ire of
