&s;hall be actually inflicted. This dread is
not confined to the vengeance of man.
For, let the &s;inner's evil deeds be ever &s;o
thoroughly concealed from the knowledge
of the world, his inward alarms are not
quieted upon that account. Now, puni&s;h|ment
is the &s;anction of a law. Every law
<PB N="388" REF="397">
&s;uppo&s;es a rightful &s;uperiour: And there|fore,
when con&s;cience threatens puni&s;h|ment
to &s;ecret crimes, it manife&s;tly recog|nizes
a &s;upreme Governour, from whom
nothing is hidden. The belief of our be|ing
